  "summary": "Upon arriving at Eustace Manor, Hercule Poirot encounters a cold reception from Mrs. Olivia and her daughter, Jane, who displays open hostility toward him. During dinner, Brent inquires about Helen Montgomery, but Mrs. Olivia claims Helen is resting after working in the garden. Later, Poirot overhears a private conversation in the ladies' lounge where Jane accuses her mother of neglecting Helen, while Mrs. Olivia dismisses Helen as a mere distant cousin and a burden to Uncle Alastair.\n\nAlistair Brent summons Poirot to his room to discuss his dissatisfaction with the official decision to halt the search for a woman named Sainsbury Silas. Brent expresses suspicion regarding a bizarre case involving a dentist's suicide and a disfigured woman named Chapman. He suspects that a woman he encountered on the steps may have orchestrated a meeting to draw attention to him. Poirot suggests the woman might be dead and explores whether Brent recalls anything unusual during his dental appointment with Mr. Moly. Brent recalls a blonde girl, an Irish dentist, and a restless young man in the waiting room, but nothing suspicious.\n\nPoirot identifies the young man as Howard Lick, a friend of Jane Olivia. He suggests that Mrs. Olivia brought Jane from America specifically to separate her from Lick, a relationship her mother disapproves of.",
